{
  "card_id": "relevant_swing_high_relevant_swing_low",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Relevant Swing High / Relevant Swing Low",
  "aliases": [
    "relevant high",
    "Relevant High",
    "relevant low",
    "Relevant Low",
    "relevant swings",
    "Relevant Swings"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "The extreme swing high or low with valid separation from adjacent swings, located within a three-higher-time-frame-candle look-back period. Unlike failure swings, these are the levels where price is expected to produce a reversal or reaction rather than continue through.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a swing point first: a bullish swing low has higher lows on both sides, a bearish swing high has lower highs on both sides.",
    "Among clustered or stacked swings, the most extreme (lowest low or highest high) is the relevant swing; closer interior swings are failure swings.",
    "Require valid separation: there must be visibly meaningful range between the swing and its nearest neighbor; if it sits too close to an unswept high/low, it is not relevant.",
    "Apply the three higher-time-frame candle look-back: include the current HTF candle plus the two prior (e.g., 3 months on daily, 3 days on hourly) and only consider swings inside that window.",
    "Prefer swings that also align with a higher-time-frame high/low (e.g., a daily relevant swing that is also a monthly high/low).",
    "When a previously relevant level fails to reverse price, the next extreme beyond it becomes the new relevant swing."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Relevant swing highs and lows are the primary points of interest for reversals and fractal-model entries; price reaching them is where to look for candle 2 / candle 3 closures, manipulation vs. breakout reads, and reactions using wick or EQ. Targets should be set toward opposing relevant swings or stacked failure swings (liquidity), while stops are best placed where there are no failure swings (high resistance liquidity) on the protected side. Random highs/lows outside the look-back or without separation should not be traded.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Trading reversals off failure swings that sit too close to an unswept extreme low/high.",
    "Treating any swing point as relevant without checking valid separation from adjacent swings.",
    "Looking back too far in history instead of limiting attention to the three-higher-time-frame-candle window.",
    "Anticipating a reversal at a level when stacked failure swings remain on the stop-loss side, providing no high resistance liquidity protection.",
    "Trying to define valid separation mechanically rather than developing discernment through chart practice."
  ],
